<p><b>Buddhism and science</b> have increasingly been discussed as compatible and <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a> has increasingly entered into the ongoing science and religion dialog.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The case is made that the philosophic and psychological teachings within Buddhism share commonalities with modern scientific and philosophic thought or at least are less at odds with them. For example, Buddhism encourages the impartial investigation of Nature (an activity referred to as <i><a href="/wiki/Dhamma_vicaya" title="Dhamma vicaya">Dhamma-Vicaya</a></i> in the <a href="/wiki/Pali_Canon" title="Pali Canon" class="mw-redirect">Pali Canon</a>) - the principal object of study being oneself.</p>
<p>With a special focus on the nature of <a href="/wiki/Mind" title="Mind">mind</a> and its implications for the concept of <a href="/wiki/Reality" title="Reality">reality</a>, Buddhism offers explanations for metaphysical issues within <a href="/wiki/Psychology" title="Psychology">psychology</a> and studies of <a href="/wiki/Consciousness" title="Consciousness">consciousness</a>. Some popular conceptions of Buddhism connect it to discourse regarding <a href="/wiki/Evolution" title="Evolution">evolution</a>, <a href="/wiki/Introduction_to_quantum_mechanics" title="Introduction to quantum mechanics">quantum theory</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Cosmology" title="Cosmology">cosmology</a>, though most scientists <a href="/wiki/Demarcation_problem" title="Demarcation problem">see a separation</a> between the religious and metaphysical statements of Buddhism and the <a href="/wiki/Scientific_method" title="Scientific method">methodology of science</a>.<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since January 2008" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup></p>
<p>Modern Buddhism has been described as rational and non dogmatic, though this is likely a modern invention and reinterpretation.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Not all forms of <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a> eschew dogmatism, remain neutral on the subject of the supernatural, or are open to scientific discoveries. Buddhism is a varied tradition and aspects include fundamentalism,<sup id="cite_ref-tub_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tub-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> devotional traditions,<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> supplication to local spirits, and various superstitions.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> Nevertheless, commonalities have been cited between scientific investigation and Buddhist thought. The <a href="/wiki/Dalai_Lama" title="Dalai Lama">Dalai Lama</a>, in a speech at the meeting of the <a href="/wiki/Society_for_Neuroscience" title="Society for Neuroscience">Society for Neuroscience</a>, listed a "suspicion of absolutes" and a reliance on causality and empiricism as common philosophical principles shared between Buddhism and science.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
